The government has ordered an immediate crackdown on foreigners who are in the country illegally owing to the threat posed by the COVID-19 pandemic. In a statement issued on Wednesday, Interior Principal Secretary Dr. Karanja Kibicho said the operation will be undertaken by the Department of Immigration and the National Police Service. The directive comes following the high number of Pakistani nationals spotted in estates in Athi River and Nairobi. PS Kibicho in the statement said majority of the Asian nationals seen in the country have originated from Pakistan and have valid Transit Visas to Saudi Arabia that are issued on arrival. “In the last four (4) months, Kenya has witnessed a surge in the number of foreign travellers transiting through our international airports. The Kenyan Government is however alarmed by the threat of the spread of the Covid-19 pandemic posed by the influx of foreign travellers transiting through the country,” reads the statement. He noted that as the crackdown continues, the goverment will henceforth restrict the number of foreigners transiting through Kenya. Also Read: “Going forward, the Government will restrict the number of foreigners transiting through the country to levels that do not pose a risk to Kenya’s national interests,” he stated. Foreigners of Pakistani origin have been reported to be arriving in the country and residing at hotels or AirBnBs around the City. Video Of The Day: Former sports CS Hassan Wario convicted over Rio games scam